# translate-loop (`t`)

Round-trip translator CLI. Installs a `t` command via pipx.

## Install

```sh
pipx install .
```

On first run, `t` creates `~/.config/t/config.json`:

```json
{ "from": "english", "to": "russian" }
```

## Usage

```sh
t <text>
t --from <lang> <text>
t --to <lang> <text>
t --from <lang> --to <lang> <text>
t -t <text>                # one-way: translate into 'from' language only
t --out ./result.txt <text>
```

`<text>` may be:

- the literal word `buffer` — reads from the system clipboard
- a filepath (auto-detected) — reads the file contents
- anything else — treated as literal text

### Default behavior (round-trip)

Translates `to → from`, then back `from → to`, and prints the result.

### `-t` mode

Skips the second hop and prints the text in the `from` language.

### `--out <path>`

Also writes the result to the given path (or `<dir>/t_output.txt` if a
directory).

Translation backend: free Google Translate via
[`deep-translator`](https://pypi.org/project/deep-translator/).
